The photothermal synergistic catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction is a sustainable approach to generate biphenyl compounds using clean and renewable solar energy. The one-step Mo doping engineering resulted in more oxygen vacancies and surface free electrons on the PrxOy surface of hollow porous nanotube morphology. Subsequently, energy-efficient and environmentally friendly catalysts (PdO/PrxOy−Moz) with higher catalytic activity were successfully prepared by deposition precipitation method. The concave and convex surfaces of the carriers could better capture visible light. Mo doping greatly extends the visible absorption range of PrxOy. More OVs defects in the PrxOy−Moz carrier inhibit the complexation of photogenerated electron-hole pairs and induce the transfer of free and photogenerated electrons to Pd. The electron-rich Pd accelerated the oxidative addition step of aryl halides to aryl phenylboronic acids, which greatly improved the catalytic performance of PdO/PrxOy−Moz in the photothermal co-catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction. Graphical abstract Metal element doping strategy to modify the surface properties of the carrier is considered as one of the effective methods to enhance the performance of Suzuki coupling reaction. The PdO/PrxOy−Moz series catalysts were successfully modified by one-step Mo doping and subsequently prepared by deposition-precipitation method loaded with Pd. The Mo doping led to a great improvement in the oxygen vacancy concentration, separation efficiency of photogenerated electrons and holes of PdO/PrxOy−Moz. The migration of photogenerated electrons to Pd is carried out while enhancing the visible light absorption of the carrier, and the electron density in the periphery of Pd is further increased. The reaction activity of the catalyst was greatly enhanced by the synergistic effect of light and heat. Among them, the PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 catalysts with higher palladium electron density showed higher catalytic performance for the Suzuki coupling reaction under low temperature visible light conditions. This finding is in line with the concept of green chemistry and sustainability. This provides a new idea for the carrier design of Pd-based catalysts and offers a wealth of possibilities for more applications of rare earth elements and transition metals in this field. Introduction Palladium (Pd)-catalyzed carbon-carbon bonding for the efficient generation of functionalized linked aryl groups has become an extremely important step in laboratory and industrial-scale organic synthesis [1]. Among them, the Suzuki-Miyaura cross-coupling reaction has attracted much attention because of its mild reaction conditions and high tolerance to a wide range of functional groups [2–5]. The Suzuki-Miyaura reaction couple aromatic halides as electrophilic reagents with aryl boronic acids to form asymmetric biphenyl compounds, which become the basis for the production of pharmaceutical intermediates and fine chemicals [3,6–8]. In the conventional thermocatalytic organic reactions, Pd is widely used as active metal for supported catalysts in the Suzuki reactions. Some carriers are capable of interfacial interactions with Pd particles, thus acting as co-catalysts and further enhancing the activity of Pd-loaded catalysts. For example, carbon materials [9,10], zeolites [11–13], metal oxides [14] and rare earth oxides [15] can be good carriers for such catalysts. With the increasing understanding of photocatalysis, more and more semiconductor materials have also started (e.g. TiO2 [16], ZnO [17], CdS [18], g-C3N4 [19], Fe2O3 [20]) to be discovered and utilized, showing great potential in the fields of environmental protection, energy conversion, and industrial catalysis. However, most conventional semiconductors absorb only the UV portion. Therefore, optimization of visible light absorption by semiconductors is important for catalytic reaction performance when designing photothermal catalysts [21]. Modifying semiconductors by introducing vacancy defects is a common strategy, which can tune their physical and chemical properties. The oxygen vancancy (OV) defect structure can enhance the light absorption range of the carrier. The separation and migration of photogenerated carriers are accelerated while suppressing electron/hole complexation [22]. Therefore, the construction of Ov in semiconductors is of great importance for photothermal catalytic systems. In lanthanide rare earth oxides, PrOx at x > 1.73 exhibits n-type semiconductor properties [23]. The researchers found that Pr6O11 exhibits different redox properties and chemical activities when doped with different cations [24–26]. The reversible conversion between Pr3+ and Pr4+ can cause changes in the content of oxygen vacancies, and these vacancy defects can be easily generated and removed from the PrxOy surface [27]. The development of novel, low-cost and environment-friendly catalysts has been a long-term goal in the field of organic synthesis, and the use of solar energy to replace fossil energy is a sustainable development strategy to achieve light energy conversion. However, most photocatalytic processes are still relatively inefficient in utilizing sunlight. The performance of photocatalysis is still limited by the low responsiveness of visible light and the high reaction energy barrier required to activate the reactants [19,28,29]. Conventional thermocatalytic conditions are not only energy intensive but also require harsh reaction conditions [3]. Photothermal catalysis, which combines the advantages of photocatalysis and thermal catalysis, has become an emerging and rapidly developing research area. This is due to the synergistic interaction between photocatalytic and thermocatalytic reaction pathways that can significantly enhance catalytic activity and modulate the catalytic pathway. In-depth understanding of photothermal synergy is the key to improve the performance of photothermal catalysis. To this end, many strategies have been developed to address the above problems, including means such as morphology modulation [30], metal element doping [31], and heterostructure construction [32]. Among these strategies, metal element doping is a fast and simple way to modify the carrier. It can change the carrier structure of the catalyst and enhance the visible light responsiveness of the carrier, thus improving the photocatalytic performance of the catalyst. Kumaravel et al. [33] investigated the effect of Mo doping on the OVs concentration and photocatalytic activity of TiO2. The substitution of Mo6+ for Ti4+ caused lattice distortion of TiO2, while Mo doping inhibited the TiO2 photogenerated electron/hole complex. The photogenerated carriers are easily trapped by Mo6+/Mo5+, thus improving the photocatalytic activity. Sun et al. [34] induced the structural distortion of [MnO6] octahedra in MnO2 by using its stronger binding energy with oxygen atoms through a high-valent Mo ion doping strategy. So that it was fully converted to Mn2+ in the energy storage process to promote the two-electron transfer reaction of Mn4+/Mn2+, and finally an aqueous zinc-manganese battery based on the two-electron transfer reaction of Mn4+/Mn2+ was realized. Lin et al. [35] increased the electrochemically active area of the material by Mo element doping and effectively modulated the electronic structure of NiCoP. The intrinsic activity of the catalytic active site was improved, and excellent HER and OER catalytic performance was obtained. Ren et al. [36]. Prepared Mo-doped Zn2SnO4(ZSO) by a one-pot hydrothermal method. The entry of Mo into the ZSO lattice promoted the generation of OVs and enhanced the separation and migration of photogenerated carriers. MZSO-x exhibited more excellent photocatalytic performance for HCHO oxidation. Rana [37] reported the synthesis of heterogeneous compounds by binding molybdenum complexes to solid carriers and investigated the catalytic activity of these compounds in various catalytic processes. Examples include the oxidation of olefins and alcohols, oxidative bromination of different substrates, and multicomponent reactions. In this paper, we present an innovative combination of Mo and PrxOy. The transition metal Mo doping was used to modulate the crystal structure and electron transfer within the variable-valence rare-earth PrxOy to enhance the catalytic activity of the catalyst in the photothermal co-catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction. PdO/PrxOy−Moz composite catalysts were successfully prepared by electrostatic spinning, high-temperature calcination and deposition precipitation methods. PrxOy−Moz carriers with thin tube walls and hollow porous structure were designed, and the hollow porous tube structure promoted the diffusion of substrate molecules and contact with the surface-active sites. Notably, the doping of Mo increased the concentration of OVs on the PrxOy surface while producing a narrow-forbidden band width and excellent photogenerated electron/hole separation efficiency, which enhanced the visible light responsiveness of the carriers. The transfer of free and photo-generated electrons to Pd accelerates the oxidative addition step of aryl halides to aryl phenylboronic acids, which greatly improves the catalytic performance of PdO/PrxOy−Moz in the photothermal co-catalytic Suzuki cross coupling reaction. The detailed methods are described in the Supporting Information (S1). Preparation of PrxOy−Moz Firstly, 0.000, 0.014, 0.028, 0.056, 0.112 g of ammonium molybdate tetrahydrate (corresponding to Mo:Pr molar ratios of 0, 5 %, 10 %, 20 %, 40 %, respectively) was dissolved in 9.000 g of DMF, and then 1.000 g of PVP-K120, 0.690 g of Pr(NO3)3·6H2O and 0.600 g of ethanol were added sequentially to the prepared solution and stirring was continued for 2 days. Until a homogeneous mixed solution was formed. The precursor solution was prepared under electrostatic spinning conditions at 20 cm and 18 kV to obtain Pr(NO3)3·6H2O-(NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O-PVP nanofibers. The nanofibers were placed in a tube furnace and pre-oxidized at 250 °C for 2 h under air atmosphere at a heating rate of 5 °C/min, and then left at 600 °C for 2 h to obtain PrxOy, PrxOy−Mo0.05, PrxOy−Mo0.1, PrxOy−Mo0.2, and PrxOy−Mo0.4 carriers. Preparation of PdO/PrxOy−Moz The PdO/PrxOy−Moz catalysts were prepared by a deposition-precipitation method [38]. Firstly, 100 mg PrxOy was suspended in a previously stirred (30 min) 40 mL Na2PdCl4 solution (9.00 mg) for 1 h. After adding 20.0 mL of previously prepared urea (urea content of about 0.200 g) solution, the solution was heated to 80 °C and kept under vigorous stirring for 4 h. The solution was cooled and placed in an ice-water bath, and 10 mL of NaBH4 solution (reducing agent content of about 1.30 mg) was added dropwise at a rate of 1 mL·min−1. After stirring in the ice water bath for 30 min, the mixed solution was aged for 3 h at room temperature. Finally, the PdO/PrxOy solid was washed three times with distilled aqueous ethanol and dried overnight at 60 °C. PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.05, PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1, PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.2 and PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.4 samples were prepared by the same method with different contents of Mo. The flow chart of sample preparation is shown in Scheme 1 . Results and discussion The morphology and structure of the catalysts were observed using scanning electron microscopy (Fig. 1 ). It can be seen in the low magnification view that all samples exhibit a fiber-like morphology, and further observed in the high magnification images that the nanotubes in fibrous morphology show a hollow porous structure, and the doping with different Mo contents does not significantly affect the morphology. The formation of hollow porous structure is caused by the difference of ethanol/DMF polarity in the precursor solution and the gas generated through the decomposition of Pr(NO3)3·6H2O during the high temperature calcination. The structures of the catalysts were further verified by TEM images (Fig. 2 (a)) and HAADF-STEM images (Fig. 2(b)). Fig. 2(c) shows that PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 has good crystallinity. The lattice spacings on the Pr6O11 (111) and (200) crystal planes were 0.316 nm and 0.273 nm, while the lattice stripes of 0.339 nm and 0.294 nm on PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 correspond to the (111) and (200) crystal planes of Pr6O11, respectively. This indicates that the doping of Mo caused the lattice expansion of PrxOy. Because the radius of Mo6+ (0.54 Å) is smaller than that of Pr3+ (1.126 Å) and Pr4+ (0.96 Å), it can easily enter the lattice of PrxOy. The 0.326 nm lattice stripe corresponds to the (111) plane of PdO crystal. EDS mapping shows that the six elements C, N, O, Pr, Mo and Pd are uniformly distributed on the catalyst, further verifying the uniform doping of Mo and the good dispersion of PdO nanoparticles. The XRD patterns of the prepared samples are shown in Fig. 3 . The diffraction peaks of PrxOy at 28.25°, 32.74°, 47.00° and 55.71°, correspond to the (111), (200), (220) and (311) crystal planes of the cubic fluorite structure Pr6O11, respectively (PDF#42–1121) [39–41]. From Fig. 1-3(a), it can be seen that with increasing Mo doping, the peaks of Pr6O11 shift to lower angles and the lattice constants were gradually increased. The broadening of the half-peak width indicates a slight decrease in the grain size of PrxOy−Moz after doping, and the introduction of Mo hinders the grain growth of PrxOy. Fig. 3(b) shows the XRD patterns of PrxOy−Moz after loading with PdO. No peaks associated with PdO were found. This may be due to the low loading of PdO or the high dispersion of PdO on the PrxOy carrier surface. The Raman spectroscopy spectra of the samples can further detect the crystal structure changes caused by the Mo doping of PrxOy, as shown in Fig. 4 (a). The peaks around 280 nm band can be assigned to O2− to Pr4+ charge transfer. The weak peak shown at 410 cm−1 belongs to the F2g vibrational mode of the cubic fluorite structure PrxOy, and the strong peak around 572 cm−1 is related to the local vibration of the oxygen defect with a wave number difference of about 160 cm−1 between the two peaks [42,43]. The A572/A425 peak area ratio is proportional to the concentration of OVs. The intensity of the F2g band peak decreases for the PdO/PrxOy−Moz series samples. (A572/A425) ratio increases, which can laterally reflect that the doping of Mo increases the concentration of OVs in PrxOy carriers. The peak at 807 cm−1 belongs to double-coordinated oxygen (Mo2 O) in asymmetric stretching mode, which is due to two MoO6 octahedral corners sharing oxygen atoms [44]. With the gradual increase of Mo doping, the wave number range of this peak gradually increases and the peak intensity is gradually enhanced, which is caused by the doping of Mo resulting in a part of MoO3 undoped into the lattice of PrxOy. Fig. 4(b) shows the H2-TPR curves of PdO/PrxOy and PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 at 50–800 °C. Two main reduction peaks can be seen at 90–280 °C and 350–600 °C. The low temperature reduction peak is due to the presence of PdO and the high temperature reduction peak is associated with the reduction of Pr4+ to Pr3+ in PrxOy [45,46]. Meanwhile, it can be observed that the reduction temperature of PdO is higher in PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 catalysts than in PdO/PrxOy catalysts, indicating that the doping of Mo enhances the interactions between PdO and PrxOy−Mo0.1, which in turn affects the electronic structure of PdO, resulting in the decrease of the electron density of PdO, and thus increases the reduction temperature of PdO. By reviewing the literature as well as comparing the data, no reduction peak of Mo was observed [47,48]. The high temperature reduction peak area of PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 catalyst is smaller compared to PdO/PrxOy. This indicates that the Pr3+ content of PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 catalyst is higher than that of PdO/PrxOy. This indicates that the Pr3+ content in PdO/PrxOy-Mo0.1 catalyst is higher than that in PdO/PrxOy. The Pr3+/Pr4+ ratio is directly proportional to the oxygen vacancy (Ov) concentration of the carrier, which suggests that the oxygen vacancy (Ov) concentration in the carrier of PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 catalyst is higher. Fig. 5 (a) shows the O 1 s high-resolution profiles of the prepared samples. The O 1 s profiles of all samples can be fitted to three peaks. The Oα, Oβ and Oγ peaks are associated with surface chemical adsorbed oxygen (hydroxyl group), surface oxygen vacancies and lattice oxygen (O2−), respectively [23,49]. The ratio of surface OVs concentration to Oβ/(Oα+Oβ+Oγ) is positively correlated, and the values of Oβ/(Oα+Oβ+Oγ) for the PdO/PrxOy, PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.05, PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1, PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.2 and PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.4 samples were 55.25 %, 57.8 %, 58.8 %, 53.76 % and 39.24 %, respectively. According to the calculation results, it can be found that the concentration of OVs in the PrxOy−Moz gradually increases with the doping of Mo. When the Mo doping amount is 20 %, a new Oδ peak appears at 530.38 eV. The Oδ peak corresponds to the lattice oxygen of MoO3, which indicates that Mo is no longer inside the lattice of PrxOy, and the generated MoO3 forms a solid solution with PrxOy. At the same time, the value of Oβ/(Oα+Oβ+Oγ) started to decrease and the concentration of carrier OVs decreased to 39.24 % when the Mo doping amount reached 40 %. This is due to the fact that the MoO3 generated by excessive Mo doping not only occupies part of the OVs defects, which also changes the catalyst carrier properties considerably. Reaction mechanism analysis Based on the experimental results, the photothermal synergistic catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction mechanism of PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 nanocomposites was postulated (Scheme 2 ). The doping of Mo in PrxOy caused the removal of some lattice oxygen atoms from the structure of PrxOy, and the concentration of OVs increased, generating more free electrons. This makes the PrxOy−Mo0.1 carrier a more excellent electron donor for electron transfer to Pd, which greatly enhances the thermocatalytic performance of PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1. Under visible illumination, the doping of Mo improves the visible light responsiveness of the catalyst carrier. PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 with more OVs defects can better suppress the complexation of photogenerated electrons and holes. It makes part of the photogenerated electrons transfer to the active metal Pd, which further increases the electron density in the periphery of Pd. In conclusion, the introduction of Mo increases the concentration of OVs in PrxOy nanocomposites, producing a narrower forbidden band width and excellent photogenerated electron/hole separation efficiency. It enables the carrier to provide more free electrons to Pd, thus improving the catalytic performance of the catalyst in the photothermal co-catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction. Conclusion In summary, we successfully introduced Mo dopant in PdO/PrxOy using electrostatic spinning technique. The reactivity of the catalyst was greatly enhanced by the synergistic effect of light and heat. It was found that substitutional doping dominates in the low-dose Mo-doped composites. The entry of Mo6+ into the lattice of PrxOy causes the lattice to swell, the oxygen vacancy concentration to increase, and the band gap to decrease. The compounding of photogenerated electron-hole pairs is suppressed while enhancing the visible light absorption of the carrier. The increased concentration of carrier OVs also generates more free electron transfer to Pd. PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.1 has a higher concentration of oxygen vacancies compared to PdO/PrxOy−Mo0.05 and PdO/PrxOy, and the photothermal catalytic performance is greatly enhanced. With the increase of Mo doping, Mo grows epitaxially to MoO3 on the surface of PrxOy and combines with PrxOy to line into solid solution. The excessive doping makes MoO3 occupy part of the vacancy defect, which hinders the separation and transmission of photoelectrons, thus leading to the decrease of catalytic activity. 10 % dose of Mo doping results in a greater concentration of oxygen vacancies in PdO/PrxOy. The separation efficiency of photogenerated electrons and holes of the carrier was greatly enhanced, inducing the transfer of photogenerated and free electrons to Pd while enhancing the visible light absorption of the carrier. The electron-rich Pd facilitates the catalytic process of the Suzuki reaction. This discovery is in line with the concept of green chemistry development. It provides more possibilities for the application of rare earth elements and transition metals in organic synthesis. coredata.dc:description: The photothermal synergistic catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction is a sustainable approach to generate biphenyl compounds using clean and renewable solar energy. The one-step Mo doping engineering resulted in more oxygen vacancies and surface free electrons on the PrxOy surface of hollow porous nanotube morphology. Subsequently, energy-efficient and environmentally friendly catalysts (PdO/PrxOy−Moz) with higher catalytic activity were successfully prepared by deposition precipitation method. The concave and convex surfaces of the carriers could better capture visible light. Mo doping greatly extends the visible absorption range of PrxOy. More OVs defects in the PrxOy−Moz carrier inhibit the complexation of photogenerated electron-hole pairs and induce the transfer of free and photogenerated electrons to Pd. The electron-rich Pd accelerated the oxidative addition step of aryl halides to aryl phenylboronic acids, which greatly improved the catalytic performance of PdO/PrxOy−Moz in the photothermal co-catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction.
